{"title_page": "Cristian P\u00e2rvulescu", "text_new": "{{BLP sources|date=April 2011}}\n'''Cristian-Romulus P\u00e2rvulescu''' (born  January 9, 1965) is a [[Romania]]n political analyst,<ref name=\"TodorovaGille2010\">{{cite book|last1=Todorova|first1=Maria|last2=Gille|first2=Zsuzsa|title=Post-Communist Nostalgia|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=rL0JgtqKwNMC&pg=PA176|accessdate=1 May 2011|date=2010-06-01|publisher=Berghahn Books|isbn=978-1-84545-671-9|page=176}}</ref> activist, journalist, and essayist. He is a professor at the [[National School of Political Studies and Public Administration]]<ref name=\"C\u00e2mpeanu2003\">{{cite book|last=C\u00e2mpeanu|first=Pavel|title=Ceau\u015fescu: the countdown|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=GTJpAAAAMAAJ|accessdate=1 May 2011|year=2003|publisher=East European Monographs|isbn=978-0-88033-524-9|page=475|quote=The attempt was made again one year later, by Cristian Parvulescu, professor at the National School of Political and Administrative Sciences, ...}}</ref> (SNSPA) in [[Bucharest]], and became its dean in December 2005.\n\nBorn in [[Ploie\u015fti]], P\u00e2rvulescu graduated in 1989 from the [[University of Bucharest]]'s Faculty of Philosophy, and went on to finish his education at the [[Paris]]-based [[Institut d'Etudes Politiques de Paris|Institut d'Etudes Politiques]] and the [[Fondation Nationale des Sciences Politiques]]. He authored his [[Ph.D.]] thesis on ''Tendencies and Evolutions in the Dynamics of the Western European Political Parties at the End of the 20th Century''.\n\nP\u00e2rvulescu is an active figure in the Romanian post-[[Romanian Revolution of 1989|1989 Revolution]] [[non-governmental organization]] scene. He has been president of [[Pro Democra\u0163ia]] since 1999, is a founding member of the Romanian Political Science Association, and counselor for the [[World Bank]] Comprehensive Development Frame Program. He has published a series of articles, studies and papers, and has taken part in a large number of seminars, debates, congresses, conferences, symposia and round tables.\n\nHe is a frequent editorialist, commentator and analyst in Romanian and foreign media including ''[[Curentul]]'', ''[[Dilema Veche|Dilema]]'', [[BBC]], [[Radio Free Europe]], [[Romanian Television Company|Romanian national television]], [[Pro TV]], [[Radio Rom\u00e2nia Actualit\u0103\u0163i]] and [[Radio Rom\u00e2nia Interna\u0163ional]]. P\u00e2rvulescu was deputy editor of the monthly ''[[Sfera Politicii]]'' between 1994 and 1997.\n\n==Political party science==\nHis early career was centered on denouncing the negative consequences of the [[Communist Romania|single-party communist regime]] that was present in Romania between 1948 and 1989, as well as of having major former second-rank [[Romanian Communist Party]] members continue holding important governmental posts (after the Communist era, the Romanian political party system was dominated by the [[National Salvation Front (Romania)|National Salvation Front]], perceived as a neo-communist party with a small faction of democrats and reformists).\n\nSeen as a reformist and a leader in democratic thought, P\u00e2rvulescu was, in the early 1990s, more and more often invited as a guest on political talk shows. What he saw as the failure of the [[Romanian Democratic Convention]] government (a [[centre-right]] coalition that governed Romania between 1996 and 2000) made him more critical of the Romanian political party system\u2014in his view, mainstream Romanian parties were more interested in immediate electoral success than in making the whole political system and the whole country work better. He also denounced the consequences of the [[party-list proportional representation|party-list electoral system]] in use in Romania, which, according to him, makes members of [[Parliament of Romania|Parliament]] more dependent on party decisions, letting them stray away from their own political beliefs in favor of \"political party discipline\". P\u00e2rvulescu attributed the apparent problems faced by the Parliament in adopting legislation to this phenomenon.\n\n==Current activities==\nAfter the [[2004 Romanian legislative election|2004 elections]], P\u00e2rvulescu, perceived by many as the most credible social and political commentator,{{Citation needed|date=February 2007}} indicated that the conflict of the two major parties in the [[Justice and Truth Alliance]] has no good effect on the [[European Union|EU]] [[Accession of Romania to the European Union|accession of 2007]].\n\nEach Sunday, he hosts on a [[TVR 1]] political [[talk show]], ''S\u0103pt\u0103m\u00e2na Politic\u0103'' (\"This Week in Politics\") and, on Saturdays, a [[Realitatea TV]] show, ''Numele meu'' (''My Name Is''), which analyzes the most recent and notorious trends and persons in politics.\n\nIn 2020, during the Covid 19 crisis, he fermly and openly expressed in national television and radio that the doctors and nurses that resign should be put in jail.  \n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Parvulescu, Cristian}}\n[[Category:Sciences Po alumni]]\n[[Category:People from Ploie\u0219ti]]\n[[Category:Romanian essayists]]\n[[Category:Romanian magazine editors]]\n[[Category:Romanian political scientists]]\n[[Category:Romanian television personalities]]\n[[Category:University of Bucharest alumni]]\n[[Category:1965 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Romanian political journalists]]\n", "text_old": "{{BLP sources|date=April 2011}}\n'''Cristian-Romulus P\u00e2rvulescu''' (born  January 9, 1965) is a [[Romania]]n political analyst,<ref name=\"TodorovaGille2010\">{{cite book|last1=Todorova|first1=Maria|last2=Gille|first2=Zsuzsa|title=Post-Communist Nostalgia|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=rL0JgtqKwNMC&pg=PA176|accessdate=1 May 2011|date=2010-06-01|publisher=Berghahn Books|isbn=978-1-84545-671-9|page=176}}</ref> activist, journalist, and essayist. He is a professor at the [[National School of Political Studies and Public Administration]]<ref name=\"C\u00e2mpeanu2003\">{{cite book|last=C\u00e2mpeanu|first=Pavel|title=Ceau\u015fescu: the countdown|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=GTJpAAAAMAAJ|accessdate=1 May 2011|year=2003|publisher=East European Monographs|isbn=978-0-88033-524-9|page=475|quote=The attempt was made again one year later, by Cristian Parvulescu, professor at the National School of Political and Administrative Sciences, ...}}</ref> (SNSPA) in [[Bucharest]], and became its dean in December 2005.\n\nBorn in [[Ploie\u015fti]], P\u00e2rvulescu graduated in 1989 from the [[University of Bucharest]]'s Faculty of Philosophy, and went on to finish his education at the [[Paris]]-based [[Institut d'Etudes Politiques de Paris|Institut d'Etudes Politiques]] and the [[Fondation Nationale des Sciences Politiques]]. He authored his [[Ph.D.]] thesis on ''Tendencies and Evolutions in the Dynamics of the Western European Political Parties at the End of the 20th Century''.\n\nP\u00e2rvulescu is an active figure in the Romanian post-[[Romanian Revolution of 1989|1989 Revolution]] [[non-governmental organization]] scene. He has been president of [[Pro Democra\u0163ia]] since 1999, is a founding member of the Romanian Political Science Association, and counselor for the [[World Bank]] Comprehensive Development Frame Program. He has published a series of articles, studies and papers, and has taken part in a large number of seminars, debates, congresses, conferences, symposia and round tables.\n\nHe is a frequent editorialist, commentator and analyst in Romanian and foreign media including ''[[Curentul]]'', ''[[Dilema Veche|Dilema]]'', [[BBC]], [[Radio Free Europe]], [[Romanian Television Company|Romanian national television]], [[Pro TV]], [[Radio Rom\u00e2nia Actualit\u0103\u0163i]] and [[Radio Rom\u00e2nia Interna\u0163ional]]. P\u00e2rvulescu was deputy editor of the monthly ''[[Sfera Politicii]]'' between 1994 and 1997.\n\n==Political party science==\nHis early career was centered on denouncing the negative consequences of the [[Communist Romania|single-party communist regime]] that was present in Romania between 1948 and 1989, as well as of having major former second-rank [[Romanian Communist Party]] members continue holding important governmental posts (after the Communist era, the Romanian political party system was dominated by the [[National Salvation Front (Romania)|National Salvation Front]], perceived as a neo-communist party with a small faction of democrats and reformists).\n\nSeen as a reformist and a leader in democratic thought, P\u00e2rvulescu was, in the early 1990s, more and more often invited as a guest on political talk shows. What he saw as the failure of the [[Romanian Democratic Convention]] government (a [[centre-right]] coalition that governed Romania between 1996 and 2000) made him more critical of the Romanian political party system\u2014in his view, mainstream Romanian parties were more interested in immediate electoral success than in making the whole political system and the whole country work better. He also denounced the consequences of the [[party-list proportional representation|party-list electoral system]] in use in Romania, which, according to him, makes members of [[Parliament of Romania|Parliament]] more dependent on party decisions, letting them stray away from their own political beliefs in favor of \"political party discipline\". P\u00e2rvulescu attributed the apparent problems faced by the Parliament in adopting legislation to this phenomenon.\n\n==Current activities==\nAfter the [[2004 Romanian legislative election|2004 elections]], P\u00e2rvulescu, perceived by many as the most credible social and political commentator,{{Citation needed|date=February 2007}} indicated that the conflict of the two major parties in the [[Justice and Truth Alliance]] has no good effect on the [[European Union|EU]] [[Accession of Romania to the European Union|accession of 2007]].\n\nEach Sunday, he hosts on a [[TVR 1]] political [[talk show]], ''S\u0103pt\u0103m\u00e2na Politic\u0103'' (\"This Week in Politics\") and, on Saturdays, a [[Realitatea TV]] show, ''Numele meu'' (''My Name Is''), which analyzes the most recent and notorious trends and persons in politics.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Parvulescu, Cristian}}\n[[Category:Sciences Po alumni]]\n[[Category:People from Ploie\u0219ti]]\n[[Category:Romanian essayists]]\n[[Category:Romanian magazine editors]]\n[[Category:Romanian political scientists]]\n[[Category:Romanian television personalities]]\n[[Category:University of Bucharest alumni]]\n[[Category:1965 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Romanian political journalists]]\n", "name_user": "188.26.41.198", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(I added a subject on recent activity)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cristian_P%C3%A2rvulescu"}
{"title_page": "Samuel Chukwueze", "text_new": "{{short description|Nigerian professional footballer|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2019}}\n{{Use Nigerian English|date=August 2019}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name = Samuel Chukwueze\n| image = Samu Chukwueze.jpg\n| caption = Chukwueze with [[Villarreal CF|Villarreal]] in 2018\n| full_name = Samuel Chimerenka Chukwueze\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1999|5|22|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Umuahia]], Nigeria\n| height = 1.72 m\n| position = [[Midfielder#Winger|Winger]]\n| currentclub = [[Villarreal CF|Villarreal]]\n| clubnumber = 11\n| youthyears1 = \n| youthclubs1 = Future Hope\n| youthyears2 = \n| youthclubs2 = New Generation Academy\n| youthyears3 = 2012\u20132017\n| youthclubs3 = Diamond Football Academy\n| youthyears4 = 2017\u20132018\n| youthclubs4 = [[Villarreal CF|Villarreal]]\n| years1 = 2018\n| clubs1 = [[Villarreal CF B|Villarreal B]]\n| caps1 = 20\n| goals1 = 4\n| years2 = 2018\u2013\n| clubs2 = [[Villarreal CF|Villarreal]]\n| caps2 = 45\n| goals2 = 8\n| nationalyears1 = 2015\n| nationalteam1 = [[Nigeria national under-17 football team|Nigeria U17]]\n| nationalcaps1 = 7\n| nationalgoals1 = 3\n| nationalyears2 = 2018\u2013\n| nationalteam2 = [[Nigeria national football team|Nigeria]]\n| nationalcaps2 = 13\n| nationalgoals2 = 2\n|medaltemplates =\n{{Medal|Competition|[[Africa Cup of Nations]]}}\n{{Medal|3rd|[[2019 Africa Cup of Nations|2019 Egypt]]|}}\n| club-update = 22:08, 19 January 2020 (UTC)\n| nationalteam-update = 20:53, 17 November 2019 (UTC)\n}}\n\n'''Samuel Chimerenka Chukwueze''' (born 22 May 1999) is a Nigerian professional [[Association football|footballer]] who plays for [[Villarreal CF]] and the [[Nigeria national football team|Nigeria national team]] as a [[Midfielder#Winger|winger]].\n\n== Early life and education ==\nChukwueze was born in [[Umuahia]] [[Abia State|Abia]] state. He is of [[Igbos|Igbo]] descent and was brought up in a Christian family with a younger brother and a younger sister. He attended [[Government College Umuahia]] and Evangel Secondary School. He started playing football at the age of 8 and he admired [[Jay-Jay Okocha]] as his football idol growing up. He has been mentored by Hon. Victor Apugo whom he saw as a father, as stated in his earlier interview.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://diamondfa.com/content/samuel-chukwueze-biography-exclusive-interview|title=Samuel Chukwueze Biography (Exclusive Interview)|date=2016-09-03|work=Diamond Football Academy Official Website|access-date=2018-11-07|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|last=Naijagood TV|title=Samuel Chukwueze Interview|date=2016-09-14|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=0C8igUmm9SI|access-date=2018-11-07}}</ref>\n[[File:Samu with victor and kelechi.png|thumb|Samuel Chukwueze with Nwakali U17 World Cup MVP award with Hon. Victor Apugo and Kelechi Nwakali with Samuel's U17 World 2015 Chile Most Valuable Player Award]]\n\n==Club career==\nBorn in Amaokwe Ugba Ibeku, [[Umuahia]], [[Abia State]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://diamondfa.com/content/samuel-chukwueze-biography-exclusive-interview|title=Samuel Chukwueze Biography (Exclusive Interview)|publisher=Diamond Football Academy|date=3 September 2016|access-date=4 October 2018}}</ref> Chukwueze joined [[Villarreal CF]]'s prolific youth setup in 2017, from local side Diamond Football Academy.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://diamondfa.com/content/samuel-chukwueze-signs-5-years-contract-villarreal-fc|title=Samuel Chukwueze signs 5 years Contract with Villarreal FC|publisher=Diamond Football Academy|date=5 September 2017|access-date=4 October 2018}}</ref> After being initially assigned to the club's ''Juvenil A'' squad, he made his senior debut with [[Villarreal CF B|the reserves]] on 15 April 2018, coming on as a second-half [[Substitute (association football)|substitute]] for [[Sergio Lozano (footballer)|Sergio Lozano]] in a 1\u20131 [[Segunda Divisi\u00f3n B]] away draw against [[CE Sabadell FC]].\n\nChukwueze scored his first senior goal on 20 May 2018, netting his team's second in a 3\u20131 away defeat of [[Bilbao Athletic]]. He contributed with two goals in 11 appearances during [[2017\u201318 Segunda Divisi\u00f3n B|his first season]], as his side missed out promotion in [[2018 Segunda Divisi\u00f3n B play-offs|the play-offs]].\n\nChukwueze made his first-team debut on 20 September 2018, replacing [[Nicola Sansone]] in a 2\u20132 home draw against [[Rangers F.C.|Rangers]], for the [[2018\u201319 UEFA Europa League]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.goal.com/en/news/samuel-chukwueze-makes-villarreal-debut-in-rangers-stalemate/t5km72czihf41fsd1y63yqhz5|title=Samuel Chukwueze makes Villarreal debut in Rangers stalemate|publisher=Goal.com|date=20 September 2018|access-date=4 October 2018}}</ref> He also made his league debut on 5 November 2018, playing a 90-minute full play in a 1\u20131 home draw against [[Levante UD|Levante]], for the [[2018\u201319 La Liga]].\n\nIn April 2019 he won the Nigeria Football Federation's 2018 Young Player of the Year award.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/47784841|title='Motivated' Samuel Chukwueze wins award ahead of Osimhen and Onyekuru|date=2 April 2019|website=BBC Sport|accessdate=27 August 2019|first=Oluwashina|last=Okeleji}}</ref>\n\n==International career==\nAfter playing for Nigeria at under-17 level, he received his first call-up to the senior team in October 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/46030232|title=Injury forces Francis Uzoho to withdraw from Nigeria squad|date=6 November 2018|website=BBC Sport|accessdate=27 August 2019|first=Oluwashina|last=Okeleji}}</ref> He made his debut for the [[Nigeria national football team|Nigerian senior team]] on 20 November 2018 as a starter in a 0\u20130 friendly draw against [[Uganda national football team|Uganda]].<ref>{{cite web|publisher=[[ESPN]]|url=http://www.espn.com/soccer/report?gameId=528097|title=Nigeria v Uganda game report|date=20 November 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/46306322|title=Samuel Chukwueze: Youngster says Nigeria debut fulfils a dream|date=22 November 2018|website=BBC Sport|accessdate=27 August 2019|first=Oluwashina|last=Okeleji}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2019, Chukwueze was invited to represent Nigeria's senior team at the [[2019 Africa Cup of Nations|Africa Cup of Nations]] and the Under-20 team at the Under-20 World Cup. However, club side Villarreal said he could only play in one of the tournaments.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/48185206|title=Samuel Chukwueze: Villarreal winger facing Nigeria dilemma|date=7 May 2019|website=BBC Sport|accessdate=27 August 2019|first=Oluwashina|last=Okeleji}}</ref> He was part of the Nigerian squad for Africa Cup of Nations hosted in Egypt.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/48574320|title=Africa Cup of Nations: Iheanacho left out of Nigeria squad|date=9 June 2019|access-date=14 June 2019|website=BBC Sport|first=Oluwashina|last=Okeleji}}</ref> He scored his first senior goal in Nigeria's 2\u20131 win over [[South Africa national football team|South Africa]] in the quarter finals.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Benson |first1=Max |title=Nigeria 2-1 Bafana - last-gasp goal as South Africa crash out of Afcon 2019 |url=https://www.thesouthafrican.com/sport/soccer/afcon-2019-live-nigeria-vs-south-africa-bafana-quarter-final |accessdate=11 July 2019 |work=The South African |date=10 July 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Playing style ==\nHe has been compared to [[Arjen Robben]] because of his skillset.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/46229240|title=Samuel Chukwueze: The Nigerian who wants to be like Arjen Robben|date=15 November 2018|website=BBC Sport|accessdate=27 August 2019}}</ref>\n\n== 50 for the future ==\nThe AFCON bronze medallist was on Tuesday, 30 July, revealed as one of the 50 youngsters to watch in world football by [https://www.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/news/newsid=2616860.html UEFA\u2019s official website], with a worth of about $33 million.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.premiumtimesng.com/sports/sports-features/344211-five-nigerian-footballers-who-must-make-sensible-transfer-decisions.html|title=Five Nigerian footballers who must make sensible transfer decisions|last=Alaka|first=Jide|work=Premium Times|date=1 August 2019|language=en-GB|access-date=24 August 2019}}</ref>\n\nTitled: 50 for the future: '''UEFA.com'''\u2019s ones to watch in 2019/20; Chukwueze, 20 was described as a \"Precocious winger with UEFA Europa League experience; the Nigeria Football Federation\u2019s young player of the year for 2017/18.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/news/newsid=2616860.html|title=50 for the future: UEFA.com's ones to watch in 2019/20|last=UEFA.com|website=UEFA.com|language=en|access-date=2019-08-09}}</ref>\n\n==Career statistics==\n===Club===\n{{updated|match played on 22 January 2020}}\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center\"\n|-\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Club\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Season\n!colspan=\"3\"|League\n!colspan=\"2\"|Cup\n!colspan=\"2\"|Other\n!colspan=\"2\"|Total\n|-\n!Division!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals\n|-\n|rowspan=\"3\"|[[Villarreal CF B|Villarreal B]]\n|[[2017\u201318 Segunda Divisi\u00f3n B|2017\u201318]]<ref name=\"SW\">{{cite web|url=https://us.soccerway.com/players/samuel-chukwueze/425644/|title=Samuel Chukwueze|publisher=Soccerway|accessdate=15 September 2019}}</ref>\n|rowspan=\"2\"|[[Segunda Divisi\u00f3n B]]\n|11||2||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||11||2\n|-\n|[[2018\u201319 Segunda Divisi\u00f3n B|2018\u201319]]<ref name=\"SW\"/>\n|9||2||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||9||2\n|-\n!colspan=\"2\"|Total\n!20!!4!!colspan=\"2\"|\u2014!!0!!0!!20!!4\n|-\n|rowspan=\"3\"|[[Villarreal CF|Villarreal]]\n|[[2018\u201319 La Liga|2018\u201319]]<ref name=\"SW\"/>\n|rowspan=\"2\"|[[La Liga]]\n|26||5||3||2||9{{efn|Appearances in [[UEFA Europa League]]|name